00:00:05.500 --> 00:00:06.650
- Good afternoon.

00:00:06.650 --> 00:00:08.109
I'm Alyssa Goodman.

00:00:08.109 --> 00:00:10.090
I'm one of the
co-directors for science

00:00:10.090 --> 00:00:12.930
here at the Radcliffe
Institute for Advanced Study.

00:00:12.930 --> 00:00:16.270
And so I have the privilege
of welcoming all of you

00:00:16.270 --> 00:00:23.470
and also welcoming the many from
the crew of the Tara vessel,

00:00:23.470 --> 00:00:26.080
which you will hear all
about this afternoon

00:00:26.080 --> 00:00:27.700
from Eric Karsenti.

00:00:27.700 --> 00:00:29.761
I'm not going to introduce Eric.

00:00:29.761 --> 00:00:31.510
I'm going to introduce
Chris Bowler, who's

00:00:31.510 --> 00:00:34.460
going to introduce Eric.

00:00:34.460 --> 00:00:38.930
And so before I
do that, I should

00:00:38.930 --> 00:00:43.190
explain that this event is
part of a series of events

00:00:43.190 --> 00:00:47.030
that goes under the general
title of "The Undiscovered."

00:00:47.030 --> 00:00:49.160
And what we mean by
"The Undiscovered,"

00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:53.090
for this year at Radcliffe, is
discoveries that are very, very

00:00:53.090 --> 00:00:54.870
hard to anticipate.

00:00:54.870 --> 00:00:58.160
So for example, you go out
to measure the deceleration

00:00:58.160 --> 00:01:01.280
of the universe with a lot of
telescopes and a lot of people.

00:01:01.280 --> 00:01:04.340
And you accidentally measure
the acceleration of the universe

00:01:04.340 --> 00:01:06.380
and win a Nobel Prize.

00:01:06.380 --> 00:01:09.950
Or you go out and
there is 15,000 species

00:01:09.950 --> 00:01:12.050
of plankton known and you
sequence a lot of stuff.

00:01:12.050 --> 00:01:14.150
And you wind up with
10 times that many.

00:01:14.150 --> 00:01:16.380
But I don't want to steal
Eric or Chris' thunder.

00:01:16.380 --> 00:01:19.280
So I won't tell you
anything more about that.

00:01:19.280 --> 00:01:21.890
What I would like to say
is that I'm really, really

00:01:21.890 --> 00:01:24.500
honored that this all came
to be and that Tara is here.

00:01:24.500 --> 00:01:26.660
And I should explain
that Chris Bowler--

00:01:26.660 --> 00:01:28.130
who I'm about to
tell you about--

00:01:28.130 --> 00:01:30.830
and I were fellows together
at the Radcliffe Institute

00:01:30.830 --> 00:01:32.210
a couple of years ago.

00:01:32.210 --> 00:01:34.730
And we knew that Tara-- the
vessel that's moored in Boston

00:01:34.730 --> 00:01:37.550
Harbor now and you
can go see it--

00:01:37.550 --> 00:01:39.440
was going to be making
this big world tour.

00:01:39.440 --> 00:01:40.939
And we thought,
wouldn't it be great

00:01:40.939 --> 00:01:43.370
if we could bring the Tara
mission here to Radcliffe,

00:01:43.370 --> 00:01:45.080
and let you hear
about it from Eric,

00:01:45.080 --> 00:01:47.840
and let you experience its
educational aspects by going

00:01:47.840 --> 00:01:48.950
to the ship?

00:01:48.950 --> 00:01:51.590
And I'm sure Eric will say
more about all of that.

00:01:51.590 --> 00:01:54.810
And so I'm just really glad
that that has come to fruition.

00:01:54.810 --> 00:01:57.590
And I invite you to come to more
of these "Undiscovered" events.

00:01:57.590 --> 00:02:00.080
And the big annual
science symposium

00:02:00.080 --> 00:02:02.360
that will cover many
topics in science

00:02:02.360 --> 00:02:05.270
